Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) was introduced to represent real-world entities and scenarios in code using objects. 
It helps developers write programs that are more organized, reusable, and easier to maintain.

The main advantage of OOP is that it increases code reusability and reduces code redundancy. 
Instead of writing the same code multiple times, we can create classes and objects and reuse them whenever required.

Functions also help in reducing redundancy and improving code reusability because a function can be called 
multiple times for repetitive tasks. However, OOP is much broader than functions. 
OOP is based on concepts such as classes, objects, inheritance, polymorphism, encapsulation, and abstraction, 
whereas a function is simply a block of code designed to perform a specific task.

Therefore, although both functions and OOP improve code reusability and reduce redundancy,
OOP cannot be considered the same as a function because it provides a complete programming paradigm for designing
and managing software systems.


